<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="1" border="0"  width="100%">
<tr>
	<td bgcolor="#262C4C" id="cat"><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF" color="#FCC504"><b><a name="29"></a>
	Starting a cleric</b></font></td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td bgcolor="#666699"><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">
	<b><font color="#FCC504">What is the best race for a cleric?</font></b><br />
<br />
There isn't a single "best race" for a cleric character; all of the races which can be clerics make fairly good ones, and there are players at the highest level of the game from all the different races. Pick a race that appeals to you and stick with it.<br />
<br />
If you really can't decide, then casual cleric players would be well advised to start a dwarf or a high elf, since these races have good starting factions and no significant drawbacks. More hardcore cleric players would find dwarf or high elf a reasonable choice as well, but might also want to consider dark elves (which have the best vision of any of the cleric races, and get some useful toys and the ability to hide, but suffer faction issues) or halflings (which can hide and sneak, and also receive an experience bonus). Roleplayers might enjoy any of the cleric races.<br />
<br />
It is particularly unusual to see very high level erudite or gnome clerics, so if you want a very unique character, you may wish to choose one of these races.<br />
<br />
<b><font color="#FCC504">How should I allocate my starting stats?</font></b><br />
<br />
1. Wisdom: Your WIS affects your total mana pool, and it is probably the most important stat for a cleric. It isn't a bad idea to put as many as 20 or 25 points into WIS on creation. However, some clerics feel that high-end cleric gear has a lot of +WIS on it already, and there are diminishing returns once your WIS passes 200, so there are arguments in favour of putting some points into other stats as well. WIS has no effect on the rate at which you regenerate mana.<br />
<br />
2. Stamina: Your STA affects how many HP you have, making it the second most important stat for a cleric. It is also relatively hard to find gear which adds STA compared to WIS or STR, so points put into STA are unlikely to be wasted.<br />
<br />
3. Strength: An issue for the weaker cleric races, and a particularly common problem for High Elves, is that they are expected to wear full plate armour but have low STR with which to carry it all around. A few points put into STR early in the game can certainly make the early levels easier.<br />
<br />
Unless there are roleplaying reasons why you wish to boost your AGI, DEX, INT, or CHA, then it is probably not a good idea to allocate starting points into these stats, which are of much less value to a cleric.</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
</td></tr></table><br>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" bgcolor="#262C4C"  width="100%" align="center"><tr><td>
<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="1" border="0"  width="100%">
<tr>
	<td bgcolor="#262C4C" id="cat"><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF" color="#FCC504"><b><a name="30"></a>
	Equipment Questions</b></font></td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td bgcolor="#666699"><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">
	<font color="#FCC504"><b>I'm a `X`-level cleric, what gear should I go for next?</b></font><br />
<br />
First, if you do not have a mana preservation focus item suitable for the highest level of spells you can cast, then it's important that you work out a way to get hold of one.<br />
<br />
If you are level 51+, the next most important thing is Flowing Thought. Flowing Thought items increase your mana regeneration rate, but almost all of them will not work if you are under level 51. There are a few tradeable Flowing Thought items - which tend to be massively expensive - and the best way to get a point of Flowing Thought is to do your Earring of the Solstice quest in the bazaar.<br />
<br />
After that, worry about your AC, your HP, and your mana pool. (STA and WIS are also relevant but only because they add to your HP and mana pool respectively).<br />
<br />
Most high end clerics agree that once your AC is over 1,000 then the returns for increasing your AC further are small. However, AC is certainly a factor for lower-level clerics. You're a cleric, not a finger-wiggler, and the sight of a cleric in a dress always makes me cringe... put yer damn plate on!<br />
<br />
As a rule of thumb, at high levels, one point of WIS is worth around 12 mana; one point of STA is worth around 3 HP. Once you have 200 in a stat, that yield is roughly halved; get past 255, and it's halved again. Items that add direct +HP and +mana may well be preferable to items that add +WIS and +STA, particularly at lower levels or very high WIS/STA totals.<br />
<br />
I'm grateful to Nyvn and Restandre for deriving the best formula we have so far on how your WIS affects your mana pool:- (Wisdom up to 200* level / 5) + (Wisdom from 201-255 * level/10) + (Wisdom-over-255*level / 13) + (raw mana) = Total mana<br />
<br />
You do not need to max out your WIS if you can get better returns with a low-WIS item. Shields of Bane Warding and Bracers of Sense are for pansy leather-wearing treehuggers, mmkay? ;P<br />
<br />
The rough principle is:-<br />
<br />
For 51+ clerics: Mana Preservation &gt; Flowing Thought &gt; HP = Mana &gt; AC = resists.<br />
For 1-50 clerics: Mana Preservation &gt; AC &gt; HP = Mana &gt; resists.<br />
<br />
<font color="#FCC504"><b>How do focus items work?</b></font><br />
<br />
Extended Range items and Buff Duration items both have a fixed benefit. Extended Range III, for example, adds 15% to the maximum range of your level 60 or lower spells and this bonus is guaranteed.<br />
<br />
Reagent Conservation items have a chance to work. Reagent Conservation III, for example, has around a 15% chance of saving you a peridot when you cast Blessing of Aegolism.<br />
<br />
All the other items add a random benefit. Mana Preservation III, for example, will reduce the mana cost of your Blessing of Aegolism spell by between 1% and 15%; over time, the effect saves you an average of 10% of your mana usage.<br />
<br />
Most focus items do not work with Complete Healing; the exception is Extended Range foci, which do affect Complete Healing. Because CH is a level 39 spell, you only need Extended Range II to get the benefit.<br />
<br />
Improved Healing focus items are not particularly valuable for a cleric unless (a) you are below level 39 or (b) you are level 65 and fighting upper-tier PoP encounters.</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
</td></tr></table><br>
